<subSubSection id="13E85C98FF92806BFF23FC32FDD6FB7F" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="5B4D0F13FF92806BFF23FC32FF4CFB8A" blockId="41.[151,255,1016,1042]" box="[151,255,1016,1042]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading id="0005B87FFF92806BFF23FC32FF4CFB8A" bold="true" box="[151,255,1016,1042]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="1">
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFF23FC32FF4CFB8A" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[151,255,1016,1042]" pageId="41" pageNumber="47" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Apoidea">
<emphasis id="6986D301FF92806BFF23FC32FF4CFB8A" bold="true" box="[151,255,1016,1042]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Apoidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4D0F13FF92806BFF23FBF5FDD6FB7F" blockId="41.[151,1436,1086,1435]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
In the past bees and sphecoid wasps have been considered as separate superfamilies, the 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFB7CFBF4FA94FBCF" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1224,1319,1086,1111]" pageId="41" pageNumber="47" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Apoidea">Apoidea</taxonomicName>
s.str. and Sphecoidea (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="3F6372E2FF92806BFED4FBA9FDA7FBE3" author="Naumann" box="[352,532,1122,1147]" firstAuthor="Naumann" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="916 - 1000" refId="ref21695" refString="Naumann, I. D. (1991) Hymenoptera &quot; wasps, bees, ants, sawflies &quot;. Chapter 42. In: I. D. Naumann, I. D. (Ed.), The Insects of Australia. CSIRO Division of Entomology, Canberra, pp. 916 - 1000." type="book chapter" year="1991">Naumann 1991</bibRefCitation>
). However, there is growing phylogenetic evidence that the bees, as a robust monophyletic group, are nested inside the sphecoid wasps (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="3F6372E2FF92806BFCEAFB4CFBC4FB07" author="Melo &amp; Goncalves" box="[862,1143,1158,1183]" firstAuthor="Melo" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="153 - 159" refId="ref21081" refString="Melo, G. A. R. &amp; Goncalves, R. B. (2005) Higher level bee classifications (Hymenoptera, Apoidea, Apidae sensu lato). Revista Brasileira de Zoologia, 22, 153 - 159. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1590 / s 0101 - 81752005000100017" type="journal article" year="2005">Melo &amp; Gonçalves 2005</bibRefCitation>
). This has been confirmed by a recent detailed molecular study by 
<bibRefCitation id="3F6372E2FF92806BFDDEFB60FCD4FB5B" author="Debevec" box="[618,871,1194,1219]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Debevec" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="527 - 535" refId="ref17181" refString="Debevec, A. H., Cardinal, S. &amp; Danforth, B. N. (2012) Identifying the sister group to the bees: a molecular phylogeny of Aculeata with an emphasis on the superfamily Apoidea. Zoologica Scripta, 41, 527 - 535. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1463 - 6409.2012.00549. x" type="journal article" year="2012">
Debevec 
<emphasis id="6986D301FF92806BFD61FB61FCA2FB5B" box="[725,785,1194,1219]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
, which places the bees (‘Anthophila’) within the 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFF23FB04FE96FB7F" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[151,293,1230,1255]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Crabronidae</taxonomicName>
, which is itself paraphyletic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="13E85C98FF92806BFF73FB39FEE8FA03" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="description">
<paragraph id="5B4D0F13FF92806BFF73FB39FEE8FA03" blockId="41.[151,1436,1086,1435]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Here we recognise two informal groups. The 
<emphasis id="6986D301FF92806BFCB3FB38FC1AFA93" bold="true" box="[775,937,1266,1291]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Spheciformes</emphasis>
(=Sphecoidea) include the 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFAB0FB38FA2BFA93" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1840" box="[1284,1432,1266,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Ampulicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ampulicidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFF23FADCFE96FAB7" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[151,293,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Crabronidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFE83FADCFE5BFAB7" authorityName="Nagy" authorityYear="1969" box="[311,488,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Heterogynaidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Heterogynaidae</taxonomicName>
(non-Australasian) and 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFCBBFADCFC31FAB7" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[783,898,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sphecidae</taxonomicName>
s.str.; and 
<emphasis id="6986D301FF92806BFBA6FADCFB23FAB7" bold="true" box="[1042,1168,1302,1327]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Apiformes</emphasis>
including all bees (= Anthophila sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="3F6372E2FF92806BFED4FAF0FDF3FACB" author="Debevec" box="[352,576,1338,1363]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Debevec" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="527 - 535" refId="ref17181" refString="Debevec, A. H., Cardinal, S. &amp; Danforth, B. N. (2012) Identifying the sister group to the bees: a molecular phylogeny of Aculeata with an emphasis on the superfamily Apoidea. Zoologica Scripta, 41, 527 - 535. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1463 - 6409.2012.00549. x" type="journal article" year="2012">
Debevec 
<emphasis id="6986D301FF92806BFE7DFAF1FDB2FACB" box="[457,513,1338,1363]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) and comprising the subfamilies Apinae, Andreninae, 
<taxonomicName id="9CF27490FF92806BFB15FAF0FAA4FACB" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[1185,1303,1338,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Colletinae">Colletinae</taxonomicName>
, Halictinae, Megachilinae, Melittinae and Stenotritinae, of which Andreninae and Melittinae do not occur in Australasia (
<bibRefCitation id="3F6372E2FF92806BFF2AFA48FEFCFA03" author="Michener" box="[158,335,1410,1435]" firstAuthor="Michener" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refId="ref21139" refString="Michener, C. D. (2000) The Bees of the World. Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, 913 pp." type="book" year="2000">Michener 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
